The decision to graduate in two years was practical: my sister began college immediately after I finished my undergraduate degree, and accelerating my degree eased my family's financial burden. This pressure to graduate early pushed me to take a large course load in my undergraduate studies. This timeline taught me to be resourceful—I learned to identify valuable research opportunities quickly, build relationships with mentors, and seek out communities where I could learn from others. Looking back, the challenge of graduating early while maintaining my research and community commitments taught me about resilience and shaped my approach to navigating challenges.

Managing this timeline while pursuing research, founding the Algorithms Club, and participating in competitive programming required persistence. Although it sometimes spread me thin, working across these areas strengthened each pursuit. The most transformative part of my undergraduate years was discovering how bringing together people with different academic backgrounds and unique perspectives created deeper understanding for everyone. In both my research and the Algorithms Club, I saw how diverse viewpoints led to better discussions and solutions. To prepare each club session, we read papers in both new and familiar areas of theoretical computer science, forcing us to engage with concepts outside our comfort zones. These discussions exposed us all to new ideas and influenced my approach to research.

In the Multimodal Interactions Lab, I introduced new students to HCI literature and research tools, helping them explore the field. In the Algorithms Club, I worked to make theoretical computer science accessible to students from computer science, mathematics, and other engineering disciplines. These experiences helped me make a positive impact on my community.

Working with people who approached problems differently—whether due to their disciplinary training, mathematical background, or research interests—often led to productive research discussions by bringing critical questions through different lenses. As a graduate student, I'm eager to continue working across subdisciplines within theoretical computer science, to mentor students encountering new research areas, and to foster inclusive problem-solving communities. The persistence and resourcefulness I developed through my accelerated timeline will serve me well, but what I value most is learning to approach research alongside others who challenge my thinking and broaden my perspective.
